# Future Integrations, Branding, and Operational Notes

This document captures planned expansion areas for the AeroLIT PXE Content image.

The current image should stay focused on one job: generate and serve PXE HTTP content. Larger orchestration workflows, such as Foreman registration, Ansible post-install configuration, DHCP, TFTP, and bootstrap orchestration, should remain outside this image unless there is a clear reason to add a small handoff point.

## Current role of this image

The PXE Content image currently provides:

```text
/boot.ipxe
/ks/*.ks
/index.html
/generated/status.json
/generated/status.txt
/generated/isos.txt
```

It dynamically builds the iPXE menu from detected ISO trees and profile definitions.

It supports:

- built-in profiles
- override profiles
- override templates
- Jinja Kickstart partials
- manual `/ks` edit preservation
- validation and health reporting
- built-in image regression tests

It does not currently own:

- DHCP configuration
- TFTP configuration
- Foreman/Katello lifecycle management
- Ansible controller setup
- post-install Ansible execution
- host inventory management
- long-term node state tracking

Those responsibilities should stay in the AeroLIT bootstrap, PXE server role, Ansible controller role, Foreman workflows, or future orchestration components.

## Future Foreman handoff notes

Foreman can eventually consume or reference this content image instead of duplicating the PXE content logic.

Possible future handoff points:

```text
/boot.ipxe
/ks/<profile>.ks
/generated/status.json
/generated/isos.txt
```

A future Foreman integration could use this image as the 芒聙聹thin PXE content layer芒聙聺 while Foreman handles host records, provisioning templates, lifecycle environments, and reporting.

Recommended future direction:

1. Keep ISO discovery and menu generation in this image.
2. Let Foreman point hosts or subnets to generated iPXE/Kickstart URLs.
3. Add optional Foreman-specific metadata only if needed.
4. Avoid making this image require Foreman to function.

A possible future metadata file could be:

```text
/generated/foreman-handoff.json
```

That file could describe detected OS versions, generated Kickstart URLs, available profiles, and suggested Foreman provisioning template values.

Do not add this until there is a real Foreman workflow ready to consume it.

## Future Ansible post-install hook notes

The current Kickstarts perform OS installation only. A future profile could add a post-install handoff to Ansible.

Possible approaches:

### Option 1: Kickstart `%post` callback

A Kickstart profile could call back to an AeroLIT endpoint after install:

```bash
curl -f http://<server>:<port>/post-install/<node-or-token>
```

This would require a real callback service outside the PXE Content image.

### Option 2: First boot systemd unit

A Kickstart could install a small first-boot unit that runs after the new system starts.

Example intent:

```text
Install OS 芒聠聮 reboot 芒聠聮 first boot service runs 芒聠聮 Ansible/bootstrap starts
```

This may be cleaner than doing too much inside Kickstart `%post`.

### Option 3: Pull-based bootstrap

A Kickstart could place a small bootstrap script on the new host. The new host then pulls configuration from the AeroLIT controller or local bundle.

This is likely the best fit for disconnected environments.

## Recommended post-install rule

Keep the PXE Content image from becoming a full automation controller.

The image may generate Kickstarts that point to post-install logic, but the actual post-install orchestration should live in:

```text
collections-hub/
bootstrap.sh
ansible_controller role
pxe_server role
future Foreman workflows
```

## Branding and menu customization

Branding should be lightweight and safe.

Current branding input:

```text
PXE_BACKGROUND_PATH=/ui/background.png
```

The generated `boot.ipxe` references the background path like this:

```ipxe
console --picture ${base}/ui/background.png --left 360 --right 360 --top 140 --bottom 140 || goto main
```

To customize branding, mount or bake in a replacement image at the configured path.

Example override idea:

```text
/etc/nginx/html/ui/background.png
```

Or set:

```bash
PXE_BACKGROUND_PATH=/ui/site-background.png
```

Then make sure the file exists under the web root.

## Menu customization

The main menu is generated from profile definitions.

To change menu entries, prefer profile overrides instead of editing `boot.ipxe` directly.

Example profile fields that affect menu text:

```yaml
profile_id: small_disk
title: Small Disk Installs
install_label: Small Disk
menu_target: small_disk
implemented: true
show_in_main_menu: true
```

Field behavior:

| Field | Menu effect |
|---|---|
| `title` | Main profile menu label |
| `install_label` | OS install option label |
| `menu_target` | iPXE target name |
| `show_in_main_menu` | Shows or hides the profile from the main menu |
| `implemented` | Controls whether real boot targets are generated |

Do not manually edit generated `boot.ipxe` as the normal customization path. It will be regenerated.

## Safe expansion rules

When adding future capability, use these rules:

1. Keep `/ks` and `boot.ipxe` generated output.
2. Put repeatable customization under `/overrides`.
3. Keep generated status files readable and useful.
4. Add validation when adding new generated content.
5. Add or update image tests when changing behavior.
6. Avoid requiring Foreman, Ansible, or DHCP for basic image functionality.
7. Avoid storing environment-specific secrets in generated status output.

## Adding future profiles

Good candidates for future implemented profiles:

```text
security_baseline
security_luks
developer_workstation
embedded_edge
```

Before flipping a placeholder profile to `implemented: true`, make sure it has:

- a profile YAML definition
- a Kickstart template
- successful test coverage
- validation results with no errors
- a clear reason for any warnings

A new implemented profile should be tested with:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

## Tagging and testing workflow

The project can publish multiple image tags from CI.

Recommended intent:

| Tag | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `test` | Easy branch or merge request testing |
| `sha-<commit>` | Exact commit traceability |
| `mr-<number>` | Merge request traceability, if enabled |
| `latest` | Promoted default branch image |

For merge request validation, test:

```text
pxe-content:test
```

After merge, consumers should normally use:

```text
pxe-content:latest
```

## What should not be added yet

Avoid adding these until there is a real consumer and test plan:

- Foreman API calls from inside this image
- Ansible execution from inside this image
- DHCP server logic inside this image
- TFTP server logic inside this image
- node inventory database logic
- secrets or tokens in generated status files

Those can be integrated later, but this image should remain useful as a simple standalone PXE HTTP content server.

